digestio: this seems to correspond to ‘ut dividat in partis’ of Orat. 137, i.e. μερισμός, rather than to ‘ut aliud alii tribuens dispertiat‘ of Orat. 138, i.e. διαίρεσις. Quint. ix. 1, 1 in his list oi figures most commonly occurring gives both digestio and distributio. The former seems to have the more general and in· definite meaning.

eontentio: ‘est per quam contraria referuntur' (ad Her. iv. 45, 58), i. e. ἀντίθεσις. The examples quoted there are ‘inimicis te placabilem, amicis inex- orabilem praebes ' and ‘vos huius incom- modis lugetis, iste rei p. calamitate laetatur: vos vestris fortunis diffiditis, iste solus suis eo magis confidit! 1. retinentia seems to include both rapitrapit or παρασιώπησις, ‘cum aliquid nos reticere dicimus, et tamen taciturn intellegitur,¹ and ἀποσιώπησις when the matter is really passed over in silence. commendatio: Quint. ix. 2, 3 ‘qui adfectus erunt vel concitati detracta voce libera et effrenatiore, iracundia, obiurgatione, optatione, exsecrationel vel illi mitiores nisi adiuvantur commenda- tione, conciliatione, ad hilaritatem im· pulsionel' Hence the' text is possibly right: but in Orat. 138 we have ‘ut denuntiet quid caveant,' hence Schiitz‘s emendation conaminatio is a very plans- ible one. Still κατάπληξις, which is supposed to be the Greek term which Cicero may be reprodacing, seems to occur only in Quint. ix. 2, 103 as an equivalent to minuet aud the meaning required is ‘warning' rather than ‘threat- ening': besides, the context in Quint. seems to imply that Cicero did not recog· nise this figure: and Quint.’s quotation in ix. 1, 31 gives contenendatio.
